BERT is an encoder-only sentence embedding transformer-based model. This has three main components, which exist in the part of encoder-only models. 
Each word of the sentence is converted into an embedding first. 
The embeddings are then appended with positional encoding that contains the information of the position of each word. 
After that, it passes through a self-attention layer, which creates a different embedding encoding the information of its neighbouring words as context.
And hence, when a sentence is converted into an embedding using BERT, it contains context aware embeddings for the whole sentence. 
This can be used in various applications like RAG or sentence cluster or sentiment analysis classification. 
Note the embedding model is often trained on a separate task altogether. For example, embedding training might happen on masked sentences or a next word prediction, 
but instead of using the whole network, you might just take the layer where the embedding is created and use that for embedding generation rather than the complete network. 
